Specific Component Recommendations:
Current	Replace With
render_signal_lane_board() with 8-12 cards	st.columns(5) + st.metric() for top KPIs
Empty "Not loaded" cards	Don't render. Show a single st.info("Load detail for more")
render_shell_snapshot() 4-tuples	st.metric() row — native Streamlit, cleaner
"Data freshness" box at top	Move to bottom or expander — it's meta, not decision data
"Snapshot is company-level..." caption	Delete. Users don't care about internal implementation.
Multiple st.caption() explanations	One line max. Put guidance in tooltip/help parameter.
Design Rules I'd Enforce:
No empty cards. If data isn't loaded, show one status line, not 9 empty placeholders.
Numbers first, explanations never. If you need to explain what a metric means, the label is wrong.
st.metric() for KPIs. It's native, accessible, and has built-in delta arrows.
Maximum 5 top-level KPIs per page. More than that and nothing stands out.
Action list > card grid for things that need human attention. A ranked list with owner + deadline > a grid of colorful boxes.
Auto-load cheap data. Gate expensive data. 24h bounded ACCOUNT_USAGE queries cost <0.001 credits. Run them on page open. Gate the 90-day scans behind buttons.
Remove all "developer documentation" from the UI. Source basis labels, freshness notes, confidence levels — these go in an expander at the bottom, not inline with the data.
Summary
The biggest UX win you can get right now:

Make shells auto-query ACCOUNT_USAGE directly (skip the mart dependency)
Replace the signal lane board with st.metric() rows that always have values
Remove empty-state card grids entirely
Put one ranked "attention needed" list under the KPIs


Current Problem
6 top-level sections that each hide 5-15 sub-workflows behind button clicks, mode selectors, and workflow pickers. A user looking for "why did my task fail" has to:

Know to click "Workload Operations"
Know to click "Load Full Detail"
Know to select "Task graphs" from a workflow picker
Then find the actual data
That's 4 clicks to answer one question. Meanwhile, the sidebar shows 6 generic labels that don't tell you what you'll find inside.

Proposed Architecture
Principle: Every sidebar item should answer ONE question. The label should BE the question.

SIDEBAR NAVIGATION:

━━━ OVERVIEW ━━━
  📊 Platform Status        ← "Is anything broken right now?"

━━━ COST ━━━
  💰 Credit Burn            ← "What are we spending?"  
  📈 Forecasting            ← "What will we spend?"
  🎯 Recommendations        ← "How do we save money?"

━━━ OPERATIONS ━━━
  ❌ Failures & Alerts      ← "What's failing?"
  🔍 Query Performance      ← "What's slow?"
  ⚙️ Tasks & Pipelines      ← "Are pipelines healthy?"

━━━ GOVERNANCE ━━━
  🔒 Security & Access      ← "Who has access to what?"
  📋 Changes & Drift        ← "What changed recently?"

━━━ DBA TOOLS ━━━
  🛠️ Action Queue           ← "What's my to-do list?"
  📝 Morning Brief          ← "What do I report to leadership?"
11 sections, each with ONE clear purpose. No sub-workflow pickers. No mode selectors. No "Load Full Detail" gates on the primary view.

Key Design Rules Per Section
Section	Opens to	Data loaded on open	Gate only
Platform Status	5 KPIs + attention list	Yes (auto, cheap)	Deep drill expanders
Credit Burn	MTD spend + top cost drivers table	Yes (metering, 24h)	90-day history
Forecasting	Trend chart + projection + anomalies	Yes (7-day trend)	90-day model
Recommendations	Ranked action list with savings	Yes (from ACCOUNT_USAGE)	One-click fix execution
Failures & Alerts	Failed queries + tasks + login failures	Yes (24h bounded)	Full error detail
Query Performance	P95 latency + spill + queue + top slow queries	Yes (24h bounded)	Query history search
Tasks & Pipelines	Task run status + failure count + SLA	Yes (24h bounded)	Task graph drill
Security & Access	Dormant users + admin usage + MFA gaps	Yes (bounded)	Full privilege audit
Changes & Drift	Recent DDL + schema changes	Yes (7-day bounded)	Full change history
Action Queue	Open items by severity + owner	Yes (from OVERWATCH table)	Closure workflow
Morning Brief	Auto-generated leadership summary	Yes (synthesized from above)	Export/copy
What This Eliminates
"Experience View" dropdown (everyone sees the same nav, role controls which items appear)
Shell → Full Workspace pattern (every page loads its own data directly)
"Load Investigation Detail" buttons as the primary interaction
Workflow selector radio buttons inside sections
"Not loaded" empty states
Signal lane boards with 8-12 cards
What About the Existing Full Workspace Sections?
Keep them — but they become the detail drill accessible via expanders or "See more" links WITHIN the new focused sections. Not separate navigation destinations.
